06662nam a22010455i 9781512823158DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815128231587 a10.9783/97815128231582doi  a(DE-B1597)627021  a(OCoLC)1304261298  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0360602bisacsh1 aBurtin, Olivier, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Nation of Veterans :bWar, Citizenship, and the Welfare State in Modern America /cOlivier Burtin. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPART I Ascent -- tChapter 1 Reform and Reaction: Veterans’ Politics in the Interwar Years -- tChapter 2 Rebirth The Veterans’ Movement in World War II -- tChapter 3 Clash: Intergenerational Transition and the Postwar Housing Crisis -- tChapter 4 Generations United: The Fight over the First Hoover Commission -- tPART II Eclipse -- tChapter 5 A House Divided: Anticommunism and Its Discontents -- tChapter 6 Consolidation and Backlash: The Korean War in the Shadow of World War II -- tChapter 7 Generations Apart: The Problem of Economic Security for Aging Veterans -- tEpilogue. The Legacies of Martial Citizenship -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA Nation of Veterans examines how the United States created the world’s most generous system of veterans’ benefits. Though we often see former service members as an especially deserving group, the book shows that veterans had to wage a fierce political battle to obtain and then defend their advantages against criticism from liberals and conservatives alike. They succeeded in securing their privileged status in public policy only by rallying behind powerful interest groups, including the Veterans of Foreign Wars, the Disabled American Veterans, and the American Legion. In the process, veterans formed one of the most powerful movements of the early and mid-twentieth century, though one that we still know comparatively little about.In examining how the veterans’ movement inscribed martial citizenship onto American law, politics, and culture, A Nation of Veterans offers a new history of the U.S. welfare state that highlights its longstanding connection with warfare. It shows how a predominantly white and male group such as military veterans was at the center of social policy debates in the interwar and postwar period and how women and veterans of color were often discriminated against or denied access to their benefits. It moves beyond the traditional focus on the 1944 G.I. Bill to examine other important benefits like pensions, civil service preference, and hospitals. The book also examines multiple generations of veterans, by shedding light on how former service members from both world wars as well as Korea and the Cold War interacted with each other.This more complete picture of veterans’ politics helps us understand the deep roots of the military welfare state in the United States today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic welfarexPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aVeteransxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteransxLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aVeteransxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteransxServices forzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteranszUnited StatesxSocieties, etc. 0aWelfare statezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aHistory-Military. 4aHistory-United States. 4aSociology-Social Movements. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisac